
@*
Procurement Tracking Tool
    CSIS 483 Capstone Project
    Moses Padilla

    Purpose:
    This page allows users to create and submit a new purchase request within the Procurement Tracking Tool. It serves as the starting point of the
    procurement workflow by collecting information required for review and approval.

    Functionality:
    - Captures vendor information.
    - Records the item being purchased.
    - Collects the estimated procurement cost.
    - Stores end-user contact information.
    - Validates required user input fields.
    - Submits purchase requests to the approval workflow.
    - Provides navigation back to the application home page.

    Notes:
    This page was developed using ASP.NET Core Razor Views, HTML5 form controls, and Bootstrap styling. HTML5 input validation techniques were
    used to ensure required information is entered before submission. Numeric validation was implemented on the Cost field to ensure users
    enter valid monetary values.

    References:
    Carey, P. M. (2020). New perspectives on HTML5 and CSS3: Comprehensive (8th ed.). Cengage Learning.

    Microsoft. (n.d.). Razor syntax reference for ASP.NET Core. https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/core/mvc/views/razor
*@


@model ProcurementTrackingTool.Models.PurchaseRequest

@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Create Purchase Request";
}

<h2>Create Purchase Request</h2>

<form asp-action="Create" method="post">

    <div class="mb-3">
        <label class="form-label">Vendor Name</label>
        <input asp-for="VendorName" class="form-control" required />
    </div>

    <div class="mb-3">
        <label class="form-label">Item Being Purchased</label>
        <input asp-for="ItemName" class="form-control" required />
    </div>

    <div class="mb-3">
        <label class="form-label">Cost</label>
        <input asp-for="Cost"
       class="form-control"
       type="number"
       step="0.01"
       min="0"
       placeholder="0.00"
       required />
    </div>

    <div class="mb-3">
        <label class="form-label">End User Name</label>
        <input asp-for="EndUserName" class="form-control" required />
    </div>

    <div class="mb-3">
        <label class="form-label">End User Email</label>
        <input asp-for="EndUserEmail" class="form-control" required />
    </div>

    <button type="submit" class="btn btn-primary">Submit Request</button>

    <a asp-action="Index" class="btn btn-secondary">Back Home</a>
</form>